ried joyful, tense, and creative sites and moments as Sufi music performances in Gujarat, Tamil graveyard processions, trans women's charitable practices, Kipling's Orientalist tales, village Kuchipudi dance performances, and Rajasthani healing shrines. Offering a synthetic and scholarly reading of wonder that speaks to the political, aesthetic, and ethical worlds of South Asia, these essays redefine the nature and meaning of wonder and its worlds. Taken together, they provide an invaluable research tool for those in the fields of Asian religion, religion in context, and South Asian religions in particular.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aWonderxReligious aspects. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Cultural Anthropology. 4aAsian Studies : India and South Asian Studies. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Comparative Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Hindu Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAllocco, Amy L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Quinn A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCopeman, Jacob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuggal, Koonal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElison, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEyssallenne, Jazmin Graves, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGold, Ann Grodzins, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHancock, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKamath, Harshita Mruthinti, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKim, Hanna H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLucia, Amanda, econtributor.